úI was wondering if I would even have enough room in my car for you.‚Äù  We both laughed at this assumption because to meet me in person is to meet someone who is almost certainly smaller.

By the time we hit Nevada I was reading George‚Äôs text messages to him and writing replies (on his cell phone).  One text message from his sister read ‚Äúwhere are you now? How is the hitchhiker?‚Äù  I wrote back ‚ÄúReno. Hitchhiker is great.‚Äù  We stopped that night in Pocatello, Idaho, and George and I split the cost of a hotel room.  Jimmy and his teenagers slept in the room next door.  I didn‚Äôt sleep too well; George turned out to be really good at snoring.  Next morning we hit the road and made excellent time, arriving in Bozeman at 11:15 am.  Those early morning starts made for good progress on the road, and before I knew it, our journey was over.  George had delivered outstanding door to door service and had been good company, plus a safe driver.  I wished him well, and without much ado he was off.

Getting back to the original intent of driving out to Montana with a stranger, the idea was to save money.  Did I accomplish this?  Between the hotel room (50% of $60) the gas, and the food, I figure I spent at least $170.  I was generous with my gas money contributions to George because let‚Äôs face it; he provided door to door service and assumed all of the wear and tear on his vehicle, plus he did all of the driving.  The absolute cheapest airfare I could find was $219-$325 each way, depending upon the date chosen (round trip airfares were equally or more expensive).  So I did save some money, not a huge amount, but I got an experience too.  Nine days later, after a great time in Bozeman, I flew home.  I thought it was kind of strange how flying took me so quickly from one place to another, there was no real transition.  The driving experience was more impressive, it provided a sense of just how big and diverse this country is.    I realized that our society has sacrificed certain aspects of the life experience for the sake of speed and the notion that time is money.  While speed and timeliness are important aspects of our contemporary lifestyles, sometimes we lose a bit of what is good in life by being hectic.  Sometimes it is good to go slowly.

Note: names of people in this story have been changed to protect their privacy
trolling craigslist for hapless victims?  Then again, he didn‚Äôt know me, so he was theoretically taking the same risk.  And how much risk are we really talking about here?  I decided the only way to delude myself into believing there was a real danger was to watch the news or perhaps a cheesy horror movie.  Rather than fall into a trap of fearing fear itself, I armed myself with knowledge.  I got to know George on the phone and decided that his personal story was either legitimate or the work of a highly sophisticated ax murderer.  In other words, he probably wasn‚Äôt making things up, but if he was then he was doing a really good job at it.  Also, I decided that I would use my camera phone to take photos of  him, his car and license plate and send these off at my earliest discretion to my girlfriend.  I figured these less than foolproof precautions constituted a reasonable insurance plan.

George turned out to be a morning person, evident in his requirement to pick me up at 6 am from my hotel room.  ( I was living out of a hotel room at the time, for that story click here ).  I noticed straight away that he was a bigger guy with lots of visible tattoos.  Uh-oh,  time to worry.  After all, it is a known fact that people with tattoos are as much as 0-100% more dangerous than people without tattoos.  Also, there were no license plates on the car, just auto dealership tags, so my camera-phone surveillance relay strategy was going to be challenged.  ‚ÄúWell heck‚Äù, I thought, as I loaded my backpack and a honeydew melon into the backseat.  At least he wasn‚Äôt kidding about moving.  The SUV was packed full of stuff.

